item.title: Former deputy national security adviser declines to show for impeachment inquiry deposition Monday
item.description: President Donald Trump's former deputy national security adviser Charles Kupperman defied a congressional subpoena Monday, failing to appear for a closed-door deposition before House impeachment investigators and throwing a new hurdle into Democrats' plans to quickly gather evidence in their inquiry.

item.title: READ: Letter from key witness's attorney saying he'll await court instruction before testifying in impeachment inquiry
Latest on Trump impeachment inquiry
Baghdadi death may be a moment of political relief for Trump but impeachment probe is not
item.description: The daring special forces raid that killed the leader of ISIS cannot have come at a better moment for a crisis-haunted President Donald Trump.

item.title: How killing a terrorist affectsÂ the impeachment inquiry into Trump
item.description: If you think something like the sensational killing by US Special Forces of the world's most wanted terrorist is going to quiet calls for President Donald Trump's impeachment, you are going to be sorely mistaken.

item.title: Baghdadi's death: More details emerge from US raid
Trump leaves key Democrats in the dark about Baghdadi raid
item.description: President Donald Trump admitted on Sunday the White House did not inform some key Democrats about the daring raid that resulted in the death of ISIS leader Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi.

item.title: Trump gets cheers, 'lock him up' chants at World Series in DC
item.description: President Donald Trump received a mix of cheers and boos as he was shown to the crowd at the World Series.

item.title: Trump equates the Smollett case to impeachment inquiry
item.description: President Donald Trump on Monday equated the case of a hate crime allegation made by actor Jussie Smollett to the current impeachment process being imposed by Congress, calling both a "scam."

item.title: Brianna Keilar: For Gold Star families, the ultimate sacrifice comes heavily taxed
item.description: In early March 2006, two days after learning her husband had died in Iraq, Malia Fry was sitting at her kitchen table in North Carolina. She was flipping through a three-ring binder with a casualty assistance officer who was shepherding her through the long list of decisions she had to make in the fog of grief.

item.title: Former North Carolina Sen. Kay Hagan dead at 66
item.description: Former US Sen. Kay Hagan of North Carolina died Monday, her family said in a statement. She was 66.

item.title: US to extend temporary protections for El Salvadorans in US for at least another year
item.description: The Trump administration will allow more than 250,000 people from El Salvador to remain in the United States under temporary status for at least one more year, the US and El Salvador governments announced Monday.

item.title: Justice Department appeals order to turn over Mueller grand jury materials
item.description: The Justice Department on Monday asked a federal judge to put on hold an order requiring the disclosure of grand jury information redacted from special counsel Robert Mueller's report to the House Judiciary Committee while it files an appeal.

item.title: The Point: Why booing Donald Trump doesn't mean what you think it means
item.description: On Sunday night, President Donald Trump went to the World Series in Washington. And got booed. Loudly. And even was subject to a "lock him up!" chant.

item.title: Sanders remembers 'dear friend' former Rep. John Conyers
item.description: Sen. Bernie Sanders remembers the late former Rep. John Conyers while speaking at a campaign rally in Detroit, the city that Conyers represented for more than 50 years.

item.title: Former Bolton deputy who was on July 25 Ukraine call caught in middle of impeachment fight
item.description: Intrigue continues to swirl around President Donald Trump's former deputy national security adviser Charles Kupperman, a key witness in the ongoing impeachment inquiry who filed a lawsuit Friday asking a federal judge to rule on whether he is obliged to testify before House investigators.

item.title: State Department official testifies he didn't know about push for Ukraine investigations
item.description: Acting Assistant Secretary of State Philip Reeker was expected to testify in the impeachment inquiry on Saturday that he did not find out there was a push by Trump administration officials for Ukraine to publicly announce investigations into Vice President Joe Biden and the 2016 election until the whistleblower complaint was made public, a source familiar with his testimony told CNN.

item.title: Judge says impeachment inquiry is legal and justifies disclosing grand jury material
item.description: A federal judge on Friday handed a major victory to House Democrats investigating President Donald Trump and ordered the Justice Department to release grand jury information redacted from special counsel Robert Mueller's investigation.

item.title: A mystery that's baffling investigators: What changed Trump's mind on $400 million in Ukraine aid?
item.description: President Donald Trump was already under fire for freezing aid to Ukraine when a Republican senator set off another alarm bell: If Trump didn't lift the hold now, Ukraine might lose the money altogether.

item.title: Feds blow door off safe, issue subpoenas as probe into Giuliani associates escalates
item.description: Federal prosecutors in New York have subpoenaed the brother of one of the recently indicted associates of Rudy Giuliani, according to two people familiar with the matter, as they escalate their investigation in the campaign-finance case.

item.title: Trump impeachment tracker: Following all the action in Congress
Biden calls Trump an 'idiot' for dismissing Russian election interference
item.description: Former Vice President Joe Biden called President Donald Trump an "idiot" for saying Russian interference in US elections is a hoax, the latest barb between the potential 2020 rivals.

item.title: Rashida Tlaib joins Ocasio-Cortez, Omar in endorsing Bernie Sanders
item.description: Michigan Rep. Rashida Tlaib endorsed Sen. Bernie Sanders for president at a rally in Detroit on Sunday night. She joins Rep. Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez of New York and Minnesota Rep. Ihan Omar in backing the Vermont independent.

item.title: 2020 Democrats mostly refrain from crediting Trump in Baghdadi's death
item.description: Following President Donald Trump's announcement on Sunday that ISIS leader Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi died during a US military raid in northwest Syria, a number of Democrats hoping to unseat him welcomed the news and congratulated US troops, but were mum on Trump's involvement in the risky operation.

item.title: From Harvard to SNL: How Pete Buttigieg and Colin Jost are crossing paths 15 years later
item.description: When Colin Jost stepped onto the Studio 8H stage in Pete Buttigieg's trademark rolled-sleeved white button down and blue tie, he wasn't just another comedian on Saturday Night Live mimicking a presidential candidate.

item.title: What's the plan? Warren's 'Medicare for All' proposal will test her brand
item.description: Elizabeth Warren says it will be ready in a "few weeks."

item.description: Ariana Grande is feelin' the bern.

item.title: Buttigieg unveils criminal justice plan as he struggles to gain traction with black voters in South Carolina
item.description: Pete Buttigieg unveiled his criminal justice plan on Saturday, coinciding with a two-day swing through South Carolina -- a state where he has struggled to gain traction with African American voters -- and his participation in a presidential candidate criminal justice forum.
